  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Unity.TextMeshPro::TMPro.TextMeshProUGUI
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: 'METRO MANILA - As another typhoon submerged several roads across Metro
    Manila, officials proudly announced that billions of pesos allocated for flood
    control had remained completely dry.


    "We can confidently say the budget
    was never in danger," one anonymous spokesperson said while standing knee-deep
    in floodwater. "Mission accomplished."



    Residents were reportedly amazed
    after discovering that several completed "flood control projects" had become
    invisible during the storm.



    "I''ve heard of ghost employees," said one
    commuter stranded on a floating jeepney. "But ghost drainage canals? That''s
    next-level innovation."



    The Department of Imaginary Infrastructure clarified
    that the missing drainage systems were part of a revolutionary Stealth Flood
    Management Program, explaining that citizens simply "lack the vision" to see
    them.



    Meanwhile, engineers pointed to a newly constructed drainage canal
    on official documents that, according to local residents, currently serves as
    "an excellent fishing spot because it doesn''t exist."



    Traffic reached
    historic levels after major roads transformed into temporary rivers, prompting
    ride-hailing apps to introduce a new vehicle category:

    Boat (Economy).

    One
    commuter shared his appreciation.



    "I left for work at 7 AM and arrived
    just in time for tomorrow."

    Local politicians quickly visited flooded communities
    wearing spotless boots and life jackets for photo opportunities before departing
    in helicopters due to "unexpected water."



    Experts predict that if flooding
    continues, Metro Manila may soon qualify as Southeast Asia''s newest island-hopping
    destination.'
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
